Class InjectiveEnumHashMap<K extends java.lang.Enum<K>,V>

  • java.lang.Object

    K - The (enum) type of the keys held by this map.

    All Implemented Interfaces:

    public class InjectiveEnumHashMap<K extends java.lang.Enum<K>,V>
extends InjectiveEnumMap<K,V>
    The InjectiveEnumHashMap is an injective map whose key values are constants from a specific enum instance and whose value-to-key mapping is maintained in a hash map.

      • InjectiveEnumHashMap

        public InjectiveEnumHashMap(InjectiveEnumMap<K,? extends V> map)
        Constructor which will create a map identical to a specified input map. The constructed map's keys will be restricted to the same enum constants as the input map, and it will be initialized with the same key-value mappings as the input map.
        Parameters:
        map - The input map to be copied.

      • InjectiveEnumHashMap

        public InjectiveEnumHashMap(java.util.Map<K,? extends V> map)
        Constructor which will create an injective map with the key and value types, as well as mappings, as a specified input map. If the input map is not an InjectiveEnumMap instance, then it must be non-empty so that the key type may be inferred. The constructor will also throw an exception if a given value exists more than once in the input map (which violates the injective map constraint that both the keys and values must be in sets).
        Parameters:
        map - The input map to base the new injective map on.
        Throws:
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - if map is empty and not an InjectiveEnumMap instance., or if map has more than one key mapping to a single value.
